    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Forms characteristic reddish-brown, erect gas-filled bladders which arise from a common base to form small patches.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_7790",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Bladders up to about 50 mm tall.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_7791",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Southern Africa and Tristan da Cunha.</p><p><u>Local/Regional: </u>Namibia to Tsitsikamma.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_7792",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Distinctive species found in patches on intertidal rocks particularly on the west coast. Commonly in sand-inundated areas.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_7793",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_7794",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>The familiar form is the gametophyte and the sporophyte phase is crustose and capable of surviving long periods buried in sand.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_7795",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Very distinctive and unlikely to be confused with any other species. The closely-related Hedgehog seaweed <i>N. erinacea</i> also sometimes also has gas filled bladders, but these are borne on flat fronds edged with numerous small lateral outgrowths (see that entry).</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_7796",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Anderson, RJ & Stegenga, H (1985). A crustose tetrasporophyte in the life history of <i>Nothogenia erinacea</i> (Turner) Parkinson (Galaxauraceae, Rhodophyta). <i>Phycologia</i>, 24, 111-118.<br><br>Anderson, RJ, Stegenga, H & Bolton, JJ (2016). Seaweeds of the South African South Coast. World Wide Web electronic publication, University of Cape Town, http://southafrseaweeds.uct.ac.za; Accessed on 22 July 2024.<br><br>Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa (Fourth edition). Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 398). <br><br>Stegenga, H, Bolton, J & Anderson, R (1997). Seaweeds of the South African west coast. <i>Contributions of the Bolus Herbarium</i>, 18. (p. 260).",
